Tracing means stepping through code line by line and tracking what each variable holds. Given:

function multiply(a, b) {
  return a * b;
}
let result = multiply(4, 5);

`multiply` is called with `4` and `5`, so inside the function `a` is `4` and `b` is `5`. The function returns `4 * 5`, which is `20`, and that value is stored in `result`.

Now trace this:

function addOne(n) {
  return n + 1;
}
let x = addOne(addOne(3));

The inner call `addOne(3)` runs first and returns `4`. That `4` becomes the input to the outer call, `addOne(4)`, which returns `5`. So `x` ends up holding `5`.

Trace this loop:

let total = 0;
for (let i = 1; i <= 4; i++) {
  total = total + i;
}

Starting with `total = 0`, the loop runs with `i` equal to `1`, `2`, `3`, then `4`. Each pass adds `i` to `total`: `0+1=1`, `1+2=3`, `3+3=6`, `6+4=10`. After the loop ends, `total` holds `10`.

Now trace:

let n = 8;
let steps = 0;
while (n > 1) {
  n = n / 2;
  steps = steps + 1;
}

`n` starts at `8`. Each pass halves `n` and adds 1 to `steps`: `8→4` (steps=1), `4→2` (steps=2), `2→1` (steps=3). Since `1 > 1` is false, the loop stops with `steps` equal to `3`.

Suppose a test repeats this block across five different test files:

await page.fill('#search-input', 'laptop');
await page.click('#search-button');
await expect(page.locator('.results-count')).toBeVisible();

The natural fix is to wrap these steps in a `SearchPage` class with a `search(term)` method and a `resultsCount` locator — turning five copies of the same selectors into a single source of truth.

class SearchPage {
  constructor(page) {
    this.page = page;
    this.input = page.locator('#search-input');
    this.button = page.locator('#search-button');
    this.resultsCount = page.locator('.results-count');
  }
  async search(term) {
    await this.input.fill(term);
    await this.button.click();
  }
}

Now every test calls `await searchPage.search('laptop')` and checks `searchPage.resultsCount` — five files' worth of selectors live in exactly one place.

Consider this test:

test('creates a project', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.fill('#project-name', 'Demo Project');
  await page.click('#create');
  await expect(page.locator('.project-list')).toContainText('Demo Project');
});

If this runs in five parallel workers at once, all five try to create a project named exactly "Demo Project". Depending on how the app handles duplicates, some runs may collide or fail for reasons that have nothing to do with a real bug.

A safer version generates a unique name per run:

test('creates a project', async ({ page }) => {
  const name = `Demo Project ${Date.now()}`;
  await page.fill('#project-name', name);
  await page.click('#create');
  await expect(page.locator('.project-list')).toContainText(name);
});

Now every parallel run creates and checks for its own uniquely named project, so the tests can't collide no matter how many run at once.

A teammate's code isn't saving new comments:

fetch('/comments', {
  method: 'POST',
  body: { text: 'Great post!' },
});

Two things are missing: there's no `Content-Type` header telling the server the body is JSON, and the body itself is a raw object — `fetch` needs a string, not an object, in the `body` field.

fetch('/comments', {
  method: 'POST',
  headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
  body: JSON.stringify({ text: 'Great post!' }),
});

Now the server receives a properly formatted JSON string and a header telling it exactly how to read it — the two pieces working together are what make the request actually succeed.
